nd, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"1350–":"1350–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1340–1392":"1340–1392","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1326–Male":"1326–Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1326":"1326","Abt 1393":"circa 1393","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","Of Eastkrick, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Elland, Halifax, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1350–":"1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1340–1392":"1340–1392","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1326–Male":"1326–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1326":"1326","Abt 1393":"about 1393","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","Of Eastkrick, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Elland, Halifax, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Eland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Elland (Yorkshire) or Little Eland (Northumberland), both of which derive their names from Old English <i>ēaland</i> ‘cultivated land by water or a river’.","Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>adel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabell Eland was born in 1350, in Elland, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John of Elland, was 24 and her mother, Isabel, was 20. She married Sir Walter de Lascelles about 1393, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1340–1392":"1340–1392","1360–1428":"1360–1428","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1326":"1326","Abt 1393":"umbes 1393","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1392":"1392","1428":"1428","Of Eastkrick, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Elland, Halifax, West Riding Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Escryck, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, En